<div class="plain-box"><h2 class="first">DNA Comparative Analysis of Schizosaccharomyces Species</h2>
<p><img src="/img/Schizo2WayAlignment.png" alt="DNA alignment between S. pombe and S. cryophilus" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px;" height="184" width="250" /></p>
<p><em>S. octosporus</em>,<em> S. cryophilus</em> and <em>S. japonicus</em> are cousins of the well studied fission yeast <em>S. pombe</em>. <!--nbsp--> <!--nbsp-->They form a broad clade, with<em> S. pombe</em> and <em>S. japonicus</em> displaying about as much conservation of protein coding sequence (~55% between core 1:1 orthologs) as humans and the chordate <em>Amphioxus</em>, or<em> Saccharomyces cerevisiae</em> and <em>Ashbya gossypii</em>. <!--nbsp--> <!--nbsp-->However, the genomes are much more similar in terms of gene content and gene order, suggesting a divergence in the rates of evolution between protein coding sequence and genome structure. <!--nbsp--> <!--nbsp-->Within the Ascomycete clade, <em>Schizosaccharomyces</em> is a deep branch, providing increased resolution for comparative studies of Ascomyces.</p>
<p>Release 21 sees the inclusion of <em>S. cryophilus</em>, <em>S. japonicus</em> and <em>S. octosporus</em> into the Ensembl Genomes browser. <!--nbsp--> <!--nbsp--> Along with the new species there are DNA alignments between all 4 <em>Schizosaccharomyce</em> species (example shown between <a href="http://fungi.ensembl.org/Schizosaccharomyces_pombe/Location/Multi?db=core;g=SPAC2F7.03c;r=I:533890-541698;r1=supercont4.1:2447837-2455645:1;s1=Schizosaccharomyces_cryophilus;t=SPAC2F7.03c.1;MultiBottom=transcript_core_pombase=transcript_label"><em>S. pombe</em> and <em>S. c</em>ryophilus</a>).</p>
